  "prompt": "How are septums pierced?",
  "response": "Septum piercing involves creating a hole through the fleshy part of the septum, which is the cartilage that separates the nostrils. Here\u2019s a general overview of the process:\n\n1. **Consultation**: Before the piercing, you'll typically have a consultation with a professional piercer. This ensures you understand the procedure, aftercare, and any potential risks.\n\n2. **Preparation**: The piercer will clean the area thoroughly to minimize the risk of infection. They often use an antiseptic solution to disinfect the nose.\n\n3. **Marking the Spot**: The piercer will use a marker to indicate where the piercing will go, ensuring that it's centered and aligned according to the client's preferences.\n\n4. **Clamping**: A specialized tool, called forceps, may be used to hold the septum in place and provide stability during the piercing.\n\n5. **Piercing**: Once everything is set, the piercer will use a hollow needle to create the piercing. The needle is pushed through the septum quickly and smoothly, minimizing pain.\n\n6. **Inserting Jewelry**: After the needle is removed, the piercer will insert the jewelry (usually a circular barbell or captive bead ring) through the new hole.\n\n7. **Aftercare Instructions**: The piercer will provide instructions for aftercare, which typically include keeping the area clean, avoiding certain activities, and noting any signs of infection.\n\n8. **Follow-up**: It's important to follow up with the piercer if there are any concerns or issues during the healing process.\n\nThe entire procedure usually takes only a few minutes and the most common placement is through the skin in the middle of the septum, but some individuals may have a different anatomy that allows for variations. Always seek out a professional piercer who adheres to proper hygiene standards to ensure a safe experience.",
